                <head>No. 1073.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bayard</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Straus</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1888-03-20">
                            <hi rend="italic">March</hi> 20, 1888</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 85.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have received your No. 64, of the 27th ultimo,
                    relative to the eviction of the cavass at the consulate of Jerusalem from his
                    residence. You state that you informally brought the complaint to the Grand
                    Vizier, “who appeared to be of the opinion that such cavass was entitled to the
                    same privileges as to domicile as are accorded to an American citizen; and he
                    immediately communicated with the governor of Jerusalem, asking for explanation
                    for the course pursued.”</p>
                <p>Your reported action is entirely in the line of, and anticipating, the
                    Department’s instruction No. 84, of the 17th instant, which directed you to
                    ascertain the customary privilege in the premises, and is therefore
                    approved.</p>
                <p>Awaiting a further report upon the subject,</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">T. F. Bayard.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
